<section xml:id="section-orthog-unitary-diag-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">

	<li>
	<title>orthogonally diagonalizable</title>
	<idx>orthogonally diagonalizable matrix</idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>unitarily diagonalizable</h></idx>
	<idx><h>diagonalizable</h><h>orthogonally</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>diagonalizable</h><h>orthogonally</h></idx>
	<p>
	a real square matrix <m>A</m> for which there exists an orthogonal matrix <m>P</m> such that
	<m>\inv{P} A P = \utrans{P} A P</m>
	is diagonal
	</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>unitarily diagonalizable</title>
	<idx>unitarily diagonalizable matrix</idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>unitarily diagonalizable</h></idx>
	<idx><h>diagonalizable</h><h>unitarily</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>diagonalizable</h><h>unitarily</h></idx>
	<p>
	a complex square matrix <m>A</m> for which there exists a unitary matrix <m>U</m> such that
	<m>\inv{U} A U = \adjoint{U} A U</m>
	is diagonal
	</p>
	</li>

	<li xml:id="definition-orthog-unitary-diag-normal">
	<title>normal matrix</title>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>normal (relative to an inner product)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>normal</h><h>matrix (relative to an inner product)</h></idx>
	<p>
	a complex square matrix which commutes with its adjoint;
	<ie /> a complex matrix <m>A</m> for which <m>\adjoint{A} A = A \adjoint{A}</m>
	</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
